    "body": "See thread at https://twitter.com/nedgar/status/929765848750977026\r\nBasically, the min timestamp calculation in `_TransformWatermarks.refresh()` is expensive due to iterating over all elements in the bundle, and is called repeatedly. By adding `get_min_timestamp` to Bundle, it need only iterate over the root elements, e.g. taking timestamp directly from _StackedWindowedValues rather than iterating over their elements.\r\nIt also memoizes the min timestamp if the bundle is committed.",

    "created_at": "2017-10-23T16:26:07Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-10-23T16:26:07Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Your correct in saying that a value may change and yet produce the same structural value. Contractually a structural value is a way for a user to provide an object which correctly implements `Object.equals` similar to Guava's EquivalenceWrapper. Since the Java SDK only is meant to rely on structural values when using Java maps and other hashcode/equals methods it should be the only thing we care to test correctly. If the user implements `Object.equals` correctly but structural value incorrectly then its likely we will not do the right thing for them since the SDK uses their type as keys in internal maps. I don't think we can do better then this for immutability testing since if we rely on other methods for checking if things are equal we won't be following the contract that matters to the SDK and that the SDK relies on.\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "created_at": "2017-10-23T16:26:07Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-10-23T16:26:07Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Your correct in saying that a value may change and yet produce the same structural value. Contractually a structural value is a way for a user to provide an object which correctly implements `Object.equals` similar to Guava's EquivalenceWrapper. Since the Java SDK only is meant to rely on structural values when using Java maps and other hashcode/equals methods it should be the only thing we care to test correctly. If the user implements `Object.equals` correctly but structural value incorrectly then its likely we will not do the right thing for them since the SDK uses their type as keys in internal maps. I don't think we can do better then this for immutability testing since if we rely on other methods for checking if things are equal we won't be following the contract that matters to the SDK and that the SDK relies on.\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "created_at": "2017-10-23T16:26:07Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-10-23T16:26:07Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Your correct in saying that a value may change and yet produce the same structural value. Contractually a structural value is a way for a user to provide an object which correctly implements `Object.equals` similar to Guava's EquivalenceWrapper. Since the Java SDK only is meant to rely on structural values when using Java maps and other hashcode/equals methods it should be the only thing we care to test correctly. If the user implements `Object.equals` correctly but structural value incorrectly then its likely we will not do the right thing for them since the SDK uses their type as keys in internal maps. I don't think we can do better then this for immutability testing since if we rely on other methods for checking if things are equal we won't be following the contract that matters to the SDK and that the SDK relies on.\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "body": "```\nimport java.lang.annotation.*;\n\n@Target({ElementType.TYPE, ElementType.FIELD, ElementType.LOCAL_VARIABLE, ElementType.METHOD, ElementType.PARAMETER})\n@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)\npublic @interface Type {\n  Class value();\n  Type[] values() default {};\n}\n```\n\nIs invalid to create via the JDK compiler but is \"constructable\". We would need to use a tool to generate the class during build time. We could prune down the ElementType target list.\n\nUsage example:\n\n```\nimport java.util.List;\nimport java.util.Map;\n\ninterface ExampleOptions {\n  @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(String.class) }) })\n  List<List<String>> getComplexList();\n\n  @Type(value=Map.class, values={ @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(String.class) }), @Type(Integer.class) })\n  Map<List<String>, Integer> getComplexMap();\n}\n```\n\nSomeone may already have defined the @Type annotation or something like it.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "The example from the CollectionSerializer I provided is more complicated but goes through the same strokes.\n\nNo example:\nContextualDeserializer {\n Deserializer() {\n }\n\n JsonDeserializer valueDeserializer;\n Deserializer(JsonDeserializer<V> valueDeserializer) {\n   this.valueDeserializer = valueDeserializer;\n }\n\n@Override createContextual(...) {\n  type = [get type from from context]\n  valueDeserializer = get value deserializer using type\n  return new Deserializer<T>(valueDeserializer);\n}\n\n@Override deserialize(...) {\n  checkState(valueDeserializer != null, \"Error message\");\n  use value deserialzer and wrap with value provider\n}\n}\n",

    "updated_at": "2016-08-17T00:43:29Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "```\nimport java.lang.annotation.*;\n\n@Target({ElementType.TYPE, ElementType.FIELD, ElementType.LOCAL_VARIABLE, ElementType.METHOD, ElementType.PARAMETER})\n@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)\npublic @interface Type {\n  Class value();\n  Type[] values() default {};\n}\n```\n\nIs invalid to create via the JDK compiler but is \"constructable\". We would need to use a tool to generate the class during build time. We could prune down the ElementType target list.\n\nUsage example:\n\n```\nimport java.util.List;\nimport java.util.Map;\n\ninterface ExampleOptions {\n  @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(String.class) }) })\n  List<List<String>> getComplexList();\n\n  @Type(value=Map.class, values={ @Type(value=List.class, values={ @Type(String.class) }), @Type(Integer.class) })\n  Map<List<String>, Integer> getComplexMap();\n}\n```\n\nSomeone may already have defined the @Type annotation or something like it.\n",

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "The example from the CollectionSerializer I provided is more complicated but goes through the same strokes.\n\nNo example:\nContextualDeserializer {\n Deserializer() {\n }\n\n JsonDeserializer valueDeserializer;\n Deserializer(JsonDeserializer<V> valueDeserializer) {\n   this.valueDeserializer = valueDeserializer;\n }\n\n@Override createContextual(...) {\n  type = [get type from from context]\n  valueDeserializer = get value deserializer using type\n  return new Deserializer<T>(valueDeserializer);\n}\n\n@Override deserialize(...) {\n  checkState(valueDeserializer != null, \"Error message\");\n  use value deserialzer and wrap with value provider\n}\n}\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
